**Doty 2006** <span style="font-size: 8pt;">(Roxanne Lynn is Associate Professor of Political Science in Arizona State University, Tempe) Millennium - Journal of International Studies 2006 35: 53 “Fronteras Compasivas and the Ethics of Unconditional Hospitality” Dec 1, 2006 http://mil.sagepub.com/content/35/1/53.citation Herm</span>

<span style="font-size: 8pt;">If one follows Derrida’s understanding of the general text as experience and writing in the broad sense as practices that signify, construct meaning, and close off meaning, then </span>Humane Borders ‘writes’ with a textual voice that weaves itself ‘so as to be effaced’.<span style="font-size: 8pt;">55 </span>Their voice may not be effaced in terms of<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> the </span>publicity <span style="font-size: 8pt;">they receive,</span> but it is effaced in terms of any possible debt owed by the recipients of their hospitality.<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> It is </span>with a certain ‘voice’ that Humane Borders speaks to those who are thirsty<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> in the desert, </span>a voice that does not demand recognition or gratitude. Theirs is the ethical work of giving to the stranger without hope of return or remuneration.<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Human Borders</span> practises a ‘writing’ that engages a double-reading of the border, a reading that carefully interprets the texts of state sovereignty and national identity,but <span style="font-size: 8pt;">that </span>simultaneously destabilises them by locating points of otherness implied in these in the form of death to the innocent others seeking only to share in what these sovereign texts purport to hold near and dear. Through the recognition of and respect for the presence and the plight of others, <span style="font-size: 8pt;">this </span>writing exhibits an unboundedness which interrupts notions of polity, justice, ethics, and hospitality which are anchored in an unquestioned allegiance to the nation-state<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> as a political, social, and cultural form </span>through which issues of legality, ethics, and rights must be posed and answered. <span style="font-size: 8pt;">I am not suggesting that Humane Borders advocates destruction of the nation-state or even completely open borders, but only that their ‘writing’ opens onto