<span style="font-size: 8pt;">If one follows Derrida’s understanding of the general text as experience and writing in the broad sense as practices that signify, construct meaning, and close off meaning, then </span>Humane Borders ‘writes’ with a textual voice that weaves itself ‘so as to be effaced’.<span style="font-size: 8pt;">55 </span>Their voice may not be effaced in terms of<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> the </span>publicity <span style="font-size: 8pt;">they receive,</span> but it is effaced in terms of any possible debt owed by the recipients of their hospitality.<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> It is </span>with a certain ‘voice’ that Humane Borders speaks to those who are thirsty<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> in the desert, </span>a voice that does not demand recognition or gratitude. Theirs is the ethical work of giving to the stranger without hope of return or remuneration.<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Human Borders</span> practises a ‘writing’ that engages a double-reading of the border, a reading that carefully interprets the texts of state sovereignty and national identity,but <span style="font-size: 8pt;">that </span>simultaneously destabilises them by locating points of otherness implied in these in the form of death to the innocent others seeking only to share in what these sovereign texts purport to hold near and dear. Through the recognition of and respect for the presence and the plight of others, <span style="font-size: 8pt;">this </span>writing exhibits an unboundedness which interrupts notions of polity, justice, ethics, and hospitality which are anchored in an unquestioned allegiance to the nation-state<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> as a political, social, and cultural form </span>through which issues of legality, ethics, and rights must be posed and answered. <span style="font-size: 8pt;">I am not suggesting that Humane Borders advocates destruction of the nation-state or even completely open borders, but only that their ‘writing’ opens onto many possibilities of which this might be one. </span>Theirs is but a momentary interruption, but an interruption nonetheless. <span style="font-size: 8pt;">The form this interruption takes is as follows. </span>Illegal immigration forces a constant re-enactment of the founding violence that establishes the nation-state and maintains its authority, but <span style="font-size: 8pt;">that </span>generally remains invisible in our awareness of life around us. <span style="font-size: 8pt;">This </span>re-enactment consists of the violence of border/immigration policies that devalue the lives of those who are ‘not us’ so as to produce ‘us’ continually.<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> While, in one sense, Humane Borders seeks to mitigate this violence through the provision of life-sustaining water, in an e</span>qually significant sense their practice demystifies the brutality necessary to maintain the illusion of our bounded democratic polity. <span style="font-size: 8pt;">In this sense water stations are moments of deconstruction happening.</span> There is an immediacy to the practice<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> of placing water in the desert. T</span>he very existence of Humane Borders is a response to a situation demanding immediate attention.<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> The </span>decision takes place with a degree of urgency. One cannot wait for the horizon of knowledge that could provide all of the historical and theoretical justifications for the decision. Such a distant vista might mean death, death at the very instant when an immediate decision is required. ‘We’re not going to wait around and let people die’,<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> says Robin Hoover. 56 </span>Justice, however unrepresentable, says Derrida, doesn’t wait. <span style="font-size: 8pt;">‘A</span> just decision is always required immediately’<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> and </span>such a decision ‘always remains a finite moment of urgency and precipitation’.<span style="font-size: 8pt;">57 But t</span>his moment of urgency and finitude exceeds itself and opens onto a ‘to come’, a justice yet to be, a venir, an incalculable justice. <span style="font-size: 8pt;">This raises the question of the temporal dimension of justice. What is its time horizon? </span>Does justice happen in just a moment or must it move along a passage to some end-point when an ultimate condition of wellbeing<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> would happen? I would argue, informed by my understanding of Derrida’s relevant writings, that </span>justice can happen in a moment.<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> Indeed</span> it must happen in a moment, the moment of madness that rends time and space.5<span style="font-size: 8pt;">8 Of course, </span>it would be desirable for immigration policies to be reformed so as to eliminate the situation that leads to deaths in the desert.<span style="font-size: 8pt;"> That too would be just. But, this does not mean that the more immediate offering of water is any less significant nor any less an instance of justice.</span>


